00:15:03,120 --> 00:15:09,280
The first thing that we talk about is this 
idea of system awareness, to be aware of the  

184
00:15:09,280 --> 00:15:16,000
system you're in and understand it, and then to 
find a novel approach within that system. Then,  

185
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:21,560
and this is often really difficult for startups, 
to be disagreeable enough to be willing to do  

186
00:15:21,560 --> 00:15:26,640
something others either can't or won't. So 
we think of subversiveness as a skill you can  

187
00:15:26,640 --> 00:15:32,240
learn. We spend a lot of time understanding 
it, talking to neuroscientists, and finding  

188
00:15:32,240 --> 00:15:37,400
examples throughout to history. It comes from 
system awareness, novelty and disagreeability. 

189
00:15:37,400 --> 00:15:44,320
One of my favorite examples of system awareness 
is a Stanford prof named Tina Seelig. She gave the  

190
00:15:44,320 --> 00:15:52,320
Stanford engineering entrepreneur class $5.00 in 
seed capital, five days to figure out what to do,  

191
00:15:52,320 --> 00:15:57,280
and two hours to do it. Then each team in the 
class would come back for three minutes and  

192
00:15:57,280 --> 00:16:02,880
present to the class and say how they had turned 
that $5.00 into the maximum revenue. It's a great  

193
00:16:02,880 --> 00:16:08,760
idea. So most people, if you ask them how to do 
that, they're going to go out and they're going to  

194
00:16:08,760 --> 00:16:13,160
buy a lottery ticket or they're going to buy some 
lemonade ingredients and set up a lemonade stand. 

195
00:16:13,160 --> 00:16:18,320
Some of these students, they're Stanford 
graduate students, they're pretty smart.  

196
00:16:18,320 --> 00:16:22,120
Some of them went and got bike pumps, and they 
offered to test people's bike pressure for free  

197
00:16:22,120 --> 00:16:25,560
and then pump it up for some money. It turns 
out they made even more money when they asked  

198
00:16:25,560 --> 00:16:28,920
for a donation. They did pretty well. They 
turned their five bucks into like 200 bucks.  

199
00:16:29,560 --> 00:16:34,560
Another class did a slightly different thing. 
They went to restaurants and stood in line at  

200
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:38,280
fancy restaurants and got the pagers and then 
sold their space in line during premium lunch  

201
00:16:38,280 --> 00:16:42,440
hours. They made about $250. It's a good 
exercise. Talk about a thing, if you want  

202
00:16:42,440 --> 00:16:45,640
to find out if your team can innovate, try 
this with your company, whether you're a big  

203
00:16:45,640 --> 00:16:49,120
company or a small company. I guarantee you 
people will suddenly realize how hard it is  

204
00:16:49,120 --> 00:16:57,480
to go to market. The winning team made $650, $605, 
somewhere in that range. You know what they did?

205
00:16:57,480 --> 00:16:58,840
I'm so curious to hear.

206
00:16:59,360 --> 00:17:00,680
What would you do?

207
00:17:00,680 --> 00:17:03,220
Oh my god, I can't even. [inaudible 00:17:03]-

208
00:17:03,220 --> 00:17:11,080
Let me recap because this is important. You got 
$5.00 in seed capital, you got five days to plan,  

209
00:17:11,080 --> 00:17:15,040
two hours to execute, and then you're going to 
present your findings in front of this class,  

210
00:17:15,040 --> 00:17:19,360
the graduate class of Stanford 
entrepreneurship for three minutes.  

211
00:17:19,360 --> 00:17:24,720
So I listed four things there. The winning 
class sold its three minutes to a company  

212
00:17:24,720 --> 00:17:30,040
that wanted to recruit Stanford grads. 
It's brilliant, right? They made an ad.

213
00:17:30,040 --> 00:17:30,480
[inaudible 00:17:30].

214
00:17:30,480 --> 00:17:34,240
What are you going to say as the professor? "Okay, 
yeah, well done," because they recognized the  

215
00:17:34,240 --> 00:17:37,800
system they were in. They took a step back 
from what they were told they had and they  

216
00:17:37,800 --> 00:17:42,440
looked at what they actually had. So I think 
that's a great example of system awareness,  

217
00:17:42,440 --> 00:17:47,960
seeing the big picture of what you're in.
Once you see the big picture, now it's time  

218
00:17:47,960 --> 00:17:52,600
to mess with things. This is the second thing, 
which is like novelty. There's a great example,  

219
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:57,720
Gymshark, which is a pretty big athleisure, 
athletic wear company in Europe, not so big  

220
00:17:57,720 --> 00:18:03,600
in North America. They're great with messing with 
social media. Right around the time that Camo came  

221
00:18:03,600 --> 00:18:11,000
out, they had a bunch of B-list celebrities wish 
a guy named Jim Shark a happy birthday. Then they,  

222
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:15,600
of course, put... I think three or four weeks 
later, Camo added 6,000 words to their terms of  

223
00:18:15,600 --> 00:18:22,000
service for consumer videos. Gymshark had all 
these celebrities wishing Jim Shark a happy  

224
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:27,040
birthday. That's like, "Hey, we noticed 
that our name was a homonym for some guy,  

225
00:18:27,040 --> 00:18:30,080
and people in North America don't 
know who we are." Is that silly? Sure. 

226
00:18:30,080 --> 00:18:37,040
Even reverse graffiti. There's companies that 
would start to spray signs on the floor, like the  

227
00:18:37,040 --> 00:18:42,080
British Intelligence Agency did a recruiting ad, 
spraying it on the sidewalk because there's no log  

228
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:47,200
against cleaning up, so they just got a spray hose 
and wrote stuff. I know these sound like silly  

229
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:53,320
ideas. Even Coinbase. Coinbase bought a 60-second 
Super Bowl ad where they bounced a QR code around  

230
00:18:53,320 --> 00:18:59,240
the screen for 60 seconds. Is it stupid? Yeah. 
They were ranked the worst of 64 Super Bowl ads.  

231
00:18:59,240 --> 00:19:04,960
But they got 20 million hits, and their servers 
fell over. So that's a novelty thing. Just seeing  

232
00:19:04,960 --> 00:19:10,400
a thing that's different, zagging when everyone 
else is zigging. So if you're aware of the system  

233
00:19:10,400 --> 00:19:16,080
and you find a novel way to do it, that's like 
two-thirds of the way to being subversive.

234
00:19:16,080 --> 00:19:20,800
A lot of these sound like they're these 
one-off marketing stunts where you probably,  

235
00:19:20,800 --> 00:19:24,840
like the Coinbase example, drive a bunch 
of traffic to your site, it's awesome,  

236
00:19:24,840 --> 00:19:28,360
you do really well, and then it kind of fades 
away. I kind of call these things turbo boosts  

237
00:19:28,360 --> 00:19:32,440
where you can just boost growth for a little 
bit and then they go away. Is there thoughts  

238
00:19:32,440 --> 00:19:37,920
you have around just the value of something 
like that versus you also need to figure out  

239
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:43,160
a way that grows your product sustainably, like a 
paid growth engine or SEO or something like that?

240
00:19:43,160 --> 00:19:48,360
Absolutely. There are lots of examples. 
I'm giving you funny examples for this.  

241
00:19:48,360 --> 00:19:52,680
But the companies that do well are the 
ones that use this kind of thinking to  

242
00:19:52,680 --> 00:19:58,640
change their value chain. Think about 
furniture. For thousands of years,  

243
00:19:59,160 --> 00:20:05,160
furniture was something that you described and 
then someone built, and then they delivered to  

244
00:20:05,160 --> 00:20:11,680
your house. That was furniture. Then IKEA went, 
"Hey, if we flat pack this stuff and change the  

245
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:16,160
design, we can put it in containers, people can 
build it themselves at home." So they took the  

246
00:20:16,160 --> 00:20:21,120
value chain of furniture creation and they 
messed with it. In that case, they delegated  

247
00:20:21,120 --> 00:20:24,960
one of the stages of furniture creation to 
someone else. That completely changed the  

248
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:31,400
furniture industry. So that's not a one-off thing.
The trick is to find these kinds of approaches  

249
00:20:31,400 --> 00:20:36,080
that are fundamental to your business 
model. For that, you have to look at,  

250
00:20:36,080 --> 00:20:41,800
how do you differentiate? Like what do you do 
for reframing? How do you change the manner in  

251
00:20:41,800 --> 00:20:45,760
which the product's delivered? Who's doing 
it? Who provides certain steps and so on?  

252
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:50,040
So we get into that a little later once 
we get beyond the idea of subversiveness.

253
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:55,480
Awesome, okay. What I love about this 
advice is helpful both for your actual  

254
00:20:55,480 --> 00:20:58,720
long-term growth strategy and 
also to just drive spikes of  

255
00:20:58,720 --> 00:21:01,320
growth when you're looking for 
ideas there [inaudible 00:21:01].

256
00:21:01,320 --> 00:21:05,520
For sure. That's one of the distinctions 
we draw. Some of these sound like growth  

257
00:21:05,520 --> 00:21:11,360
hacks. I'm not a big fan of growth hacks. A 
growth hack traditionally is sort of product  

258
00:21:11,360 --> 00:21:15,760
agnostic. So when you move your mouse off the 
screen and it pops up a little window saying,  

259
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:21,800
"Hey, why are you leaving?" there was a time that 
was cool. Now that mouse doesn't care what kind  

260
00:21:21,800 --> 00:21:26,440
of website you are. We like the term zero-day 
marketing exploits because it's the difference  

261
00:21:26,440 --> 00:21:30,520
between a script kiddie and a proper hacker. 
In this case, it's like the difference between  

262
00:21:30,520 --> 00:21:36,080
a growth hacker and someone who is genuinely 
trying to subvert the dynamics of the industry  

263
00:21:36,080 --> 00:21:42,160
they're in. That takes a very big perspective.
I'll give you another example that I love. There's  

264
00:21:42,160 --> 00:21:48,840
a researcher named Zachary Hambrick who did 
some work with sailors as the Navy was trying to  

265
00:21:48,840 --> 00:21:56,920
restructure how it hired. He gave the sailors this 
dashboard. It had four quadrants. One corner was a  

266
00:21:56,920 --> 00:22:00,920
fuel gauge, and when it got to a level, you had to 
press a button. One was add two numbers together.  

267
00:22:00,920 --> 00:22:06,040
One was like some word thing. One was press a 
tone. In the middle was a scoreboard. So your  

268
00:22:06,040 --> 00:22:10,720
job was to monitor these four consoles and try and 
maximize your score. So as soon as it needed your  

269
00:22:10,720 --> 00:22:16,600
attention, you'd attend to it. Then unbeknownst 
to these sailors, about halfway through the test,  

270
00:22:16,600 --> 00:22:21,440
he changed the scoring so that one of 
the four quadrants represented 75% of  

271
00:22:21,440 --> 00:22:28,640
the points. So now doing the math would get 
you more points. Some of the sailors changed  

272
00:22:28,640 --> 00:22:32,000
their behavior. They recognized this one 
thing was contributing more. They hammered  

273
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:38,920
on it and they'd do really well. Other sailors 
did what they were told, super conscientious. 

274
00:22:38,920 --> 00:22:44,680
Now, the Navy has always recruited in the 
military people who do what they're told  

275
00:22:44,680 --> 00:22:50,200
and are super conscientious. Turns out the people 
that don't do that, we call them disagreeable. We  

276
00:22:50,200 --> 00:22:55,880
say they're sloppy. But there's a difference 
here between people who are playing the game  

277
00:22:55,880 --> 00:23:01,320
right and people who are questioning 
whether they're playing the right game. 

278
00:23:01,320 --> 00:23:07,120
One of the things I love as an example of 
this is poker. In poker there are rules.  

279
00:23:07,120 --> 00:23:12,800
The rules tell you which cards win, which hands 
are stronger, whose turn of play it is. But the  

280
00:23:12,800 --> 00:23:16,880
strength of your cards isn't how you win in poker. 
If that's how we played, it would just be a game  

281
00:23:16,880 --> 00:23:23,800
of statistics and it would be incredibly boring. 
You win by bluffing. You win by subterfuge. You  

282
00:23:23,800 --> 00:23:29,520
win by looking for your opponent's tells. But 
we never talk about that in business school. 

283
00:23:29,520 --> 00:23:37,040
There's this woman from the 1600s. Her name is 
Deu-la-Deu Martins. She was married to the king  

284
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:44,080
of a city state who went to war. She was left 
behind to guard the castle. The enemy shows up,  

285
00:23:44,080 --> 00:23:48,360
and the castle is pretty well fortified. She 
realizes they have about two weeks worth of food,  

286
00:23:48,360 --> 00:23:52,640
and then they're going to get captured. So she 
rounds up all the flour in the castle. She bakes  

287
00:23:52,640 --> 00:23:56,880
a bunch of bread. She goes up to the parapets, 
and she throws it over into the awaiting army  

288
00:23:56,880 --> 00:24:02,920
and says, "You look hungry. Let us know if 
you need some more food." And the army leaves. 

289
00:24:02,920 --> 00:24:07,360
That's a very valid strategy, but we don't 
talk about those kinds of strategies. Was  

290
00:24:07,360 --> 00:24:12,360
it evil? No. Was it clever? Yeah. The coat 
of arms of this town is two crossed loaves  

291
00:24:12,360 --> 00:24:18,160
of bread. But we don't talk about that kind of 
thinking in business and in startups enough. I  

292
00:24:18,160 --> 00:24:24,000
think I'd like to normalize this kind of 
disagreeable thinking, this idea that...  

293
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:28,680
I know from listening to your Evan LaPointe 
podcast that you're high on agreeable thinking,  

294
00:24:28,680 --> 00:24:32,560
so I'm here to tell you, you need to 
embrace some disagreeability, Lenny.

295
00:24:32,560 --> 00:24:37,440
I'm glad that you're here to help me there. This 
also reminds me of my chat with Rory Sutherland,  

296
00:24:37,440 --> 00:24:43,240
who's extremely good at this. One very 
tactical piece of advice he had is spend  

297
00:24:43,240 --> 00:24:47,800
a lot of time on doing the things everyone 
all agrees on is the smart thing to do.  

298
00:24:47,800 --> 00:24:50,520
Then once you've done that, set time 
aside to do the things that are very  

299
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:54,354
irrational and crazy. Thoughts on that just 
as a way to find time [inaudible 00:24:54].

300
00:24:54,354 --> 00:24:58,320
Well, I love Rory. In fact, Emily and 
I are meeting him in London for dinner.

301
00:24:58,320 --> 00:24:59,000
Amazing.

302
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:02,148
He read the book and said some 
very nice things about it.

303
00:25:02,148 --> 00:25:02,160
I love that.

304
00:25:02,160 --> 00:25:08,680
I think Rory's example of the wine list, which 
you've probably heard, the wine list is a system.  

305
00:25:08,680 --> 00:25:12,200
I can't sell you a gin and tonic for 50 bucks 
because you know how much it costs to make one.  

306
00:25:12,200 --> 00:25:18,120
But I can sell you wine for any price because you 
can't make it that way. But when someone shows up  

307
00:25:18,120 --> 00:25:23,920
at the table with a wine list and hands it to 
the most powerful looking person at the table  

308
00:25:23,920 --> 00:25:30,160
who opens it and says, "Red or white?" you 
have now all consented to order wine. So the  

309
00:25:30,160 --> 00:25:35,520
wine industry and the wine in a restaurant is a 
system, and you're beholden to it. I think Rory,  

310
00:25:35,520 --> 00:25:41,320
more than maybe anyone in the world... I asked 
Emily who her perfect... who would she want to  

311
00:25:41,320 --> 00:25:45,000
read this book if it was anyone, and she said 
"Rory." I think more than anyone in the world,  

312
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:49,960
he just sees the world through these 
system lenses that are incredible.

313
00:25:49,960 --> 00:25:53,840
I love this idea of zero-day exploits 
that you've mentioned a couple times.  

314
00:25:53,840 --> 00:25:57,320
Is there anything else there just as a 
way to think about how to come up with  

315
00:25:57,320 --> 00:26:00,080
clever ideas to grow your product and business?

316
00:26:00,080 --> 00:26:04,240
I would say, once you've got the subversive 
mindset, which again is like system awareness,  

317
00:26:04,240 --> 00:26:09,960
novelty and disagreeability, then you have 
to kind of scan the market. We have this  

318
00:26:09,960 --> 00:26:16,240
framework called the Recon Canvas that splits 
the market up into the product, the medium,  

319
00:26:16,240 --> 00:26:20,320
and the market. That's another hot take of mine 
is I think that product market fit's overrated.  

320
00:26:20,320 --> 00:26:25,040
You have to actually think about product medium 
market fit. Marketing textbooks were written in  

321
00:26:25,040 --> 00:26:31,400
a time when the medium was one-way, one-to-many 
paid broadcast. That's completely changed. Today,  

322
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:37,120
it's any-to-any. It's perfectly valid to build an 
audience first, then figure out what to sell it,  

323
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:41,880
then make the product. But we still talk about 
product market fit. Two companies with the  

324
00:26:41,880 --> 00:26:46,800
same product sold to the market, one wins and the 
other doesn't. It's often because of their medium  

325
00:26:46,800 --> 00:26:51,480
strategy. The medium is both the platforms 
you're in and the norms of that platform. 

326
00:26:51,480 --> 00:26:59,360
So we have this thing called the Recon Canvas that 
helps you scan across the product, the market,  

327
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:02,760
and the medium. If you want inspiration 
for some clever ideas, I think Burger  

328
00:27:02,760 --> 00:27:07,640
King is better than almost anybody at this 
stuff. When they launched their mobile app,  

329
00:27:07,640 --> 00:27:11,040
the thing you want for your mobile app is you 
want as many installs as possible and you want  

330
00:27:11,040 --> 00:27:18,680
geolocation turned on. So they said, "Everyone can 
have a free Whopper, just order it from the app,  

331
00:27:18,680 --> 00:27:22,920
drive to the store, and pick it up. But the catch 
is you got to order it from a McDonald's parking  

332
00:27:22,920 --> 00:27:28,520
lot." That's genius, right? They also edited the 
Wikipedia page for the description of the Whopper,  

333
00:27:28,520 --> 00:27:33,960
and then made all the home speakers go read it by 
making an ad that said, "Hey, okay, Google, what's  

334
00:27:33,960 --> 00:27:39,080
in a Whopper?" They do a whole bunch of things.
But a great example of their understanding of  

335
00:27:39,080 --> 00:27:46,640
the medium, in 2019, they started liking all 
these posts from influential posters from 10  

336
00:27:46,640 --> 00:27:51,480
years before, and they offered no explanation. 
People are like, "Hey, Burger King, why are you  

337
00:27:51,480 --> 00:27:55,600
liking my old posts?" Because the reality is 
if someone likes your posts from 10 years ago,  

338
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:59,960
it's either a bot, a stalker, or you're about 
to get sued. It's probably one of those three  

339
00:27:59,960 --> 00:28:05,440
things. So Burger King starts liking these 
things. Now, if Burger King had just liked that  

340
00:28:05,440 --> 00:28:09,040
person's latest post, they would've missed it. 
Someone likes one of your posts, you have enough  

341
00:28:09,040 --> 00:28:13,120
followers that it may get lost in the noise. But 
if it's something from 10 years ago, because of  

342
00:28:13,120 --> 00:28:18,360
the mechanics of the platform, you'll see it.
Burger King says nothing. Influencers start  

343
00:28:18,360 --> 00:28:23,200
getting upset, "What's going on? What's going 
on?" Then finally the reveal, they say, "Hey,  

344
00:28:23,200 --> 00:28:26,800
we've been liking some things from 10 years ago 
because sometimes the past is great. You know  

345
00:28:26,800 --> 00:28:32,440
what else is great? Funnel cake fries and we're 
bringing them back." Millions of free impressions,  

346
00:28:32,440 --> 00:28:36,440
not just because they understood that they had 
a funny message, but because they understood  

347
00:28:36,440 --> 00:28:40,840
the mechanism of the platform, that by liking 
something from the past, someone would notice  

348
00:28:40,840 --> 00:28:45,360
it. So understanding the mechanics of the 
platform, the norms of the platform and what  

349
00:28:45,360 --> 00:28:49,640
are done there is so important to a got-to-market 
strategy these days, but we think it often gets  

350
00:28:49,640 --> 00:28:55,320
overlooked. So to answer your question, I think 
scanning for opportunities across product, across  

351
00:28:55,320 --> 00:28:59,680
market and across medium, and we spend a lot of 
time in the book talking about how to do that.

352
00:28:59,680 --> 00:29:04,920
This Recon Canvas, I know it's hard to visualize 
a canvas grid thing, and we'll link to it in the  

353
00:29:04,920 --> 00:29:08,360
show notes, but just to help people get a 
better sense of what they're going to be  

354
00:29:08,360 --> 00:29:13,040
thinking about to scan the market, there's 
three columns, is that how you describe it?

355
00:29:13,040 --> 00:29:16,280
Yeah. The canvas actually has three rows.

356
00:29:16,280 --> 00:29:17,640
Three rows.

357
00:29:17,640 --> 00:29:22,000
That's because there's an objective, a collective, 
and a subjective way to look at the world. Then  

358
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:27,720
it has a section for product, which we 
divide into the features and the messages,  

359
00:29:27,720 --> 00:29:33,240
a section for the medium, which is the platforms 
and the norms, and then a section for the market,  

360
00:29:33,240 --> 00:29:39,000
which is the attention you capture and 
the actions you create. So it's a really  

361
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:41,920
good checklist when you're putting 
together your go-to-market strategy.  

362
00:29:41,920 --> 00:29:46,240
Make sure you've thought about all of 
those, what winds up being 18 squares.

363
00:29:46,240 --> 00:29:49,000
The idea is you look within each 
of these cross-sections to see  

364
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:52,033
if there's an opportunity to do something a 
little subversive and [inaudible 00:29:52].

365
00:29:52,033 --> 00:29:53,520
Right. You go into each square and you say,  

366
