00:44:30,040 --> 00:44:35,440
They had these gigantic stick figure semaphores 
that they would pivot to send messages. Basically,  

549
00:44:35,440 --> 00:44:38,560
you'd sit there and you'd look, and when that 
semaphore moved, you'd write down the message and  

550
00:44:38,560 --> 00:44:43,240
you'd send it to the next one. This way a message 
could travel across France at like 500 miles an  

551
00:44:43,240 --> 00:44:49,880
hour, way faster than a horse. It's great.
Of course, because there's an advantage here,  

552
00:44:49,880 --> 00:44:55,600
some bankers figured out how to pay off the 
Chappe telegraph operator to introduce an  

553
00:44:55,600 --> 00:45:01,360
error in the message in Paris which would allow 
the person in the stock market in Burgundy to  

554
00:45:01,360 --> 00:45:07,640
know what the Paris markets are doing before the 
news got there and trade on it. That is too evil.  

555
00:45:07,640 --> 00:45:16,400
But can you find out in advance of something?
Early on in the days of certain social platforms,  

556
00:45:16,400 --> 00:45:22,280
the analysts were all trying to figure out, 
were they actually seeing growth? It turns out  

557
00:45:22,280 --> 00:45:27,320
that in some of the early social platforms, 
you could look at the number of the message  

558
00:45:27,320 --> 00:45:33,760
or the number of the user's account in the API, 
and you could infer growth from that. The data's  

559
00:45:33,760 --> 00:45:38,400
right there. Is that illegal? Not really. It's 
right there, but it's certainly an advantage.  

560
00:45:38,400 --> 00:45:45,080
So what can you find out early that others can't?
Now, a more concrete example, this is Farmville.  

561
00:45:45,840 --> 00:45:52,480
Pincus and Zuckerberg were very good friends. 
Zuckerberg told Pincus that apps were going to  

562
00:45:52,480 --> 00:45:59,000
be allowed to post to user's timelines. This is 
why Farmville grew almost overnight. At one point,  

563
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:04,400
it represented a massive proportion of Facebook's 
revenue is that Farmville would post these things  

564
00:46:04,400 --> 00:46:09,040
saying, "Hey, Lenny, Alistair needs your help 
getting some grain for his cows or they're  

565
00:46:09,040 --> 00:46:15,160
going to die." So there's a good example of 
knowing something before other people did.

566
00:46:15,160 --> 00:46:19,200
I also think about the high-frequency trading and 
the arbitrage they found of just moving closer to  

567
00:46:19,200 --> 00:46:23,920
the data centers and just buying land right next 
door to where the trading [inaudible 00:46:24].

568
00:46:23,920 --> 00:46:28,200
There's actually a case of the Nikkei 
terminals, which computed the Nikkei  

569
00:46:28,200 --> 00:46:34,040
index. They weren't getting the Nikkei index 
from Tokyo. It was being computed locally on  

570
00:46:34,040 --> 00:46:38,600
the terminal. Someone figured this out so they 
could compute the Nikkei index from the source  

571
00:46:38,600 --> 00:46:43,160
stocks rather than waiting for the terminal to 
tell them, and they could beat the market for a  

572
00:46:43,160 --> 00:46:48,640
significant amount of time. Rob also told us, 
I think it was him, he said, "A hedge fund is  

573
00:46:48,640 --> 00:46:55,840
an organization formed to discover something 
that will be illegal and do it until it is."

574
00:46:55,840 --> 00:47:00,440
Yep. Makes me think about billions, 
which feels a lot of evil.

575
00:47:00,440 --> 00:47:02,080
Yeah, absolutely.

576
00:47:02,080 --> 00:47:03,960
Cool. Let's do a few more.

577
00:47:03,960 --> 00:47:09,720
Aggregation, this is a pattern we see over and 
over again where one player in the market takes  

578
00:47:09,720 --> 00:47:15,880
data from many places and then modifies it in 
some way. That could be that they are using it for  

579
00:47:15,880 --> 00:47:20,520
affiliate links, that's pretty easy, or selling 
the data, not that interesting. One of my favorite  

580
00:47:20,520 --> 00:47:25,440
examples, and I actually helped put together a 
case study at HBS when I was teaching there with  

581
00:47:25,440 --> 00:47:31,075
Srikant Datar, about a guy named LP Maurice. 
I think you might know LP. He's a Montrealer.

582
00:47:31,075 --> 00:47:31,080
I do.

583
00:47:31,080 --> 00:47:38,240
He had a company called Busbud. LP was traveling 
the length of South America, and he was trying to  

584
00:47:38,240 --> 00:47:44,440
find bus schedules, and they're almost impossible 
to get. So when he got home, he decided to make an  

585
00:47:44,440 --> 00:47:48,800
app so you could order, kind of like Kayak for 
bus rides, which doesn't sound that exciting,  

586
00:47:48,800 --> 00:47:54,560
but bus tickets are a multi-billion dollar 
industry. So he got people around the world  

587
00:47:54,560 --> 00:47:58,360
to send in these bus schedules. He put them all 
in one place. Then he went to the bus companies  

588
00:47:58,360 --> 00:48:02,800
and said, "Hey, how about you let me sell bus 
tickets?" None of them wanted to hear from him. 

589
00:48:02,800 --> 00:48:09,160
So what he did was he used automation 
to create thousands and thousands,  

590
00:48:09,160 --> 00:48:15,120
I think it's millions and millions of pages of bus 
tables, properly structured JSON data. You had to  

591
00:48:15,120 --> 00:48:18,520
automate this thing. I think you actually had 
to get three separate Google Analytics accounts  

592
00:48:18,520 --> 00:48:24,600
to manage all the data because it was beyond the 
capacity of one of them. Then for search engines,  

593
00:48:24,600 --> 00:48:28,920
this is like catnip, like well-structured data 
that's not available everywhere else. So now  

594
00:48:28,920 --> 00:48:34,600
he becomes the default destination because he's 
aggregated the data for a particular kind of data,  

595
00:48:34,600 --> 00:48:39,920
bus ticket data. Then he allows you to go in and 
say, "I want to go from here to here," shows you  

596
00:48:39,920 --> 00:48:43,880
the route. But the bus companies still aren't 
going to pay him money. So he puts a button on,  

597
00:48:43,880 --> 00:48:48,040
it says, "Buy my ticket," and sends them 
to those companies. Then the next time he  

598
00:48:48,040 --> 00:48:51,000
calls the companies, he goes, "Hey, have 
you noticed on your analytics that 20%  

599
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:55,360
of your traffic is coming from me? We should 
probably talk." Now they're willing to trade. 

600
00:48:55,360 --> 00:49:01,960
So aggregating data, consolidating it, putting 
the bait out there like the catnip for the  

601
00:49:01,960 --> 00:49:07,080
search engine or whatever. Sometimes this can be 
done badly. One of the examples we think is too  

602
00:49:07,080 --> 00:49:12,960
evil is Get Satisfaction. Get Satisfaction 
was a complaint site on the internet where,  

603
00:49:12,960 --> 00:49:17,560
basically, they went and crawled the internet 
for all the complaints about Sony, and then  

604
00:49:17,560 --> 00:49:21,120
that's the first place you're going to complain 
about Sony. Then they'd extort Sony and say,  

605
00:49:21,120 --> 00:49:24,720
"Unless you buy from us, we're going to tell the 
customers you don't care about them." Probably  

606
00:49:24,720 --> 00:49:29,920
too evil. You shouldn't assume consent. But that 
pattern of aggregation shows up time, and again.

607
00:49:29,920 --> 00:49:33,560
It's interesting there's a trend across all 
these examples you're giving, which is you're  

608
00:49:33,560 --> 00:49:39,080
solving actual problems for people in different 
ways, and you're finding a new way to solve that  

609
00:49:39,080 --> 00:49:43,000
problem or help them be aware that you're solving 
this problem. In this case of the bus schedules,  

610
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:47,440
people really want that information, like Google 
wants it, but also people want schedules that are  

611
00:49:47,440 --> 00:49:50,480
easy to read, and you've just found a really 
interesting way to get [inaudible 00:49:51].

612
00:49:50,480 --> 00:49:56,360
Almost every one of these tactics looks awesome 
in hindsight. Some of these are very basic things.  

613
00:49:56,920 --> 00:50:00,400
One of the most basic marketing tactics, and Rory 
can talk about this better than I ever could,  

614
00:50:00,400 --> 00:50:05,680
is reframing. When you look at positioning, 
you're looking at two dimensions. Let's say for  

615
00:50:05,680 --> 00:50:14,480
toothpaste, you have the dimension of sex appeal, 
"Fresh breath lasts all night," that was Colgate,  

616
00:50:14,480 --> 00:50:18,200
then you have the dimension of clinicality, which 
is like, "Four of five dentists agree," that was  

617
00:50:18,200 --> 00:50:23,000
Crest. So in the early toothpaste wars, you had 
Colgate versus Crest. You were either brushing  

618
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:26,640
your teeth because you want to be sexy or brushing 
your teeth because you wanted to be healthy.  

619
00:50:28,080 --> 00:50:34,760
Then along comes Tom's of Maine. Remember, this is 
1970s, you got your tofu from a health food store.  

620
00:50:34,760 --> 00:50:41,280
Dr. Strangelove has lines about fluoride being 
a government conspiracy. So you show up and go,  

621
00:50:41,280 --> 00:50:46,920
"Oh, we're unfluoridated. We're natural. We'll 
tell you the ingredients on the label." You've  

622
00:50:46,920 --> 00:50:53,880
given a segment of the market a different, 
better way to think about the value you offer. 

623
00:50:53,880 --> 00:50:59,600
Reframing isn't just about competing on existing 
dimensions. It's about giving the customer a  

624
00:50:59,600 --> 00:51:04,400
different set of dimensions. That won't happen 
for the whole market, but it'll happen for one  

625
00:51:04,400 --> 00:51:11,720
of those segments. In this case, the framing was 
orthogonal. If you are a hippie natural person,  

626
00:51:11,720 --> 00:51:18,000
you reject clinical science and you reject 
traditional beauty norms, so you're orthogonal,  

627
00:51:18,760 --> 00:51:24,520
you're perpendicular to both sex appeal 
and healthcare. So it's a perfect position,  

628
00:51:24,520 --> 00:51:28,440
and Tom's of Maine used that and, obviously, two 
years later introduced a fluoridated formula and  

629
00:51:28,440 --> 00:51:34,160
got into grocery stores or into pharmacies.
So being able to reframe things. I mentioned  

630
00:51:34,160 --> 00:51:38,320
Liquid Death. But when people talk about 
positioning, they often look at the dimensions  

631
00:51:38,320 --> 00:51:42,160
of that are there and say, "How do we compete on 
those?" or they go, "Hey, we're really good at  

632
00:51:42,160 --> 00:51:45,720
this thing. Let's make that the dimension." 
The dimension only matters if a lucrative,  

633
00:51:45,720 --> 00:51:52,480
reachable target market thinks that it is the 
dominant criteria for deciding about the product.

634
00:51:52,480 --> 00:51:54,480
And is reframing one of the 
tactics [inaudible 00:51:55]?

635
00:51:54,480 --> 00:51:56,680
Yep, reframing would be one 
of the tactics for sure.

636
00:51:56,680 --> 00:52:00,000
Okay, awesome. Is it interchangeable with  

637
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:01,880
positioning, or do you think of 
those two [inaudible 00:52:02]?

638
00:52:01,880 --> 00:52:08,360
We actually think that positioning is simply where 
you are on a grid. Reframing is drawing the grid.

639
00:52:08,360 --> 00:52:12,320
Got it. I have an awesome episode with 
April Dunford, who's I think also Canadian-

640
00:52:12,320 --> 00:52:12,440
Yep.

641
00:52:12,440 --> 00:52:15,400
... where she goes deep into positioning. 
I think she'd probably disagree with you  

642
00:52:15,400 --> 00:52:18,120
because I think to her it's 
really important that when  

643
00:52:18,120 --> 00:52:21,880
you're positioning, you're thinking about 
your competitors and how you're different.

644
00:52:21,880 --> 00:52:26,880
I would argue that you can position 
against your competitors. It is far better  

645
00:52:26,880 --> 00:52:33,480
for someone to choose you instead of rather than 
over your competitors. When the electric car came  

646
00:52:33,480 --> 00:52:39,640
out, the traditional framing for electric cars 
was range and sustainability. Then Tesla started  

647
00:52:39,640 --> 00:52:47,640
racing them against Bugattis. For a certain 
segment of the market, meaning rich coastal VCs,  

648
00:52:47,640 --> 00:52:51,640
faster, better performance was a new way 
to think of electric cars. Before that,  

649
00:52:51,640 --> 00:52:55,400
if you look at the ads from the Prius and 
stuff, they didn't mention acceleration  

650
00:52:55,400 --> 00:53:01,280
time. They explicitly didn't put it 
in there. So Tesla came up with a  

651
00:53:01,840 --> 00:53:09,480
much better dimension for a certain target 
segment. I agree, April's absolutely right,  

652
00:53:09,480 --> 00:53:13,440
if you're in an established competitive market 
where you're bidding for RFPs and B2B. But  

653
00:53:13,440 --> 00:53:19,520
if you're disagreeing with the market, you're 
probably disagreeing with how it scores value.

654
00:53:19,520 --> 00:53:22,400
You were talking about fluoride briefly. My 
mind went to, I'm trying to decide if fluoride  

655
00:53:22,400 --> 00:53:26,600
is actually good or bad for our kid. There's so 
many debates out there for [inaudible 00:53:27].

656
00:53:26,600 --> 00:53:29,920
As a British person with all my 
teeth, it's served me very well.

657
00:53:29,920 --> 00:53:33,480
Okay, that's my current position. It 
feels like a good thing, but there's  

658
00:53:33,480 --> 00:53:35,560
so much stuff out there. Ah, no 
fluoride [inaudible 00:53:35].

659
00:53:35,560 --> 00:53:38,320
Well, let me talk to you about regulation.

660
00:53:38,320 --> 00:53:39,040
Ooh.

661
00:53:39,040 --> 00:53:43,960
Regulation is like a thing people often don't 
think about. In Germany and in Austria, you have  

662
00:53:43,960 --> 00:53:47,880
organ donor cards where you get to approve whether 
or not someone gets your organs if you're killed  

663
00:53:47,880 --> 00:53:53,120
in an accident. German and Austrian populations 
are almost identical. Austria's opt out. You're  

664
00:53:53,120 --> 00:53:58,520
going to deliver your organs when you die unless 
you explicitly say you don't want to. In Germany,  

665
00:53:58,520 --> 00:54:03,200
you have to opt in. They're not donated 
unless you explicitly do so. Germany has  

666
00:54:03,200 --> 00:54:10,320
12% organ donors. Austria has like 99.6%. So 
all your growth hacks ain't going to get you  

667
00:54:10,320 --> 00:54:18,920
from 12% to 99.6%. So it may be important for 
your business to change the regulations either  

668
00:54:18,920 --> 00:54:24,640
to allow what you're doing or to compel people 
to do the thing that's currently optional.  

669
00:54:24,640 --> 00:54:30,040
But a lot of startups don't look at regulatory 
change as a viable strategy, and yet it can be. 

670
00:54:30,040 --> 00:54:34,440
It's also a great way to find loopholes. 
I love the story of parklets. For a while,  

671
00:54:34,440 --> 00:54:40,360
urban agitators would build these little two-hour 
long parks in the parking spot in front of their  

672
00:54:40,360 --> 00:54:43,960
coffee shop, and every two hours they'd take 
it away and put it back because the law didn't  

673
00:54:43,960 --> 00:54:47,560
actually say it had to be a car that was parked 
there. Then there's this guy in England who said,  

674
00:54:47,560 --> 00:54:51,320
"I want to make a little park in front of 
my house," but the law says it has to be a  

675
00:54:51,320 --> 00:54:57,480
car. So he built a park on a car. Then 
the local town government said, "Well,  

676
00:54:57,480 --> 00:55:00,840
you're going to have to take your car in and get 
it smog checked once a year, so it's not going  

677
00:55:00,840 --> 00:55:11,040
to last." So he bought this historical van that 
was not required to be smog checked. So he just  

678
00:55:11,040 --> 00:55:15,840
has a park in front of his house that's the 
back of a van parked there. Loopholes happen  

679
00:55:15,840 --> 00:55:19,320
all the time. We think they're funny, we think 
they're clever, but there are a lot of cases  

680
00:55:19,320 --> 00:55:26,440
where you can find a loophole and use that to do 
something possible that wasn't otherwise possible.

681
00:55:26,440 --> 00:55:29,520
Let me see how many we've gone through so far. 
I'm just going to go through the list so far,  

682
00:55:29,520 --> 00:55:35,480
and I'm curious if there's anything else. 
Turning bugs into features, upgrading,  

683
00:55:35,480 --> 00:55:42,840
buyer upgrade, access, bait and 
switch, combination, arbitrage,  

684
00:55:42,840 --> 00:55:48,240
aggregation, reframing, and regulation, 
I think, was the last one you shared.

685
00:55:48,240 --> 00:55:52,720
Then earlier on we talked about misappropriation 
with Netflix, misappropriating the US Postal  

686
00:55:52,720 --> 00:55:57,080
Service. Then the last one is sliding the window. 
Sliding the window is a bit more nebulous,  

687
00:55:57,080 --> 00:56:03,320
but it's about the Overton window and the realm of 
what's considered acceptable. A lot of companies  

688
00:56:03,320 --> 00:56:08,560
have strategies that rely on a certain segment 
of the market being okay with something that  

689
00:56:08,560 --> 00:56:12,960
wasn't. So we talk about some examples of 
the normalization of gay marriage through  

690
00:56:12,960 --> 00:56:18,240
Will & Grace and things like that in there.
There's a good example of this. There's a  

691
00:56:18,240 --> 00:56:24,480
company in England, I think it's called Bodyform, 
that was the first to use red liquid in ads for  

692
00:56:24,480 --> 00:56:30,680
female hygiene products and tampon products. 
For a while it was literally illegal to use red  

693
00:56:30,680 --> 00:56:37,280
liquids in those ads. When they finally did it, 
all the women were like... I'm telling Emily's  

694
00:56:37,280 --> 00:56:40,760
version of the story. One of the nice things 
about having a female co-author, you get to see  

695
00:56:40,760 --> 00:56:44,760
a whole other perspective that isn't normally 
part of a lot of marketing conversations. But  

696
00:56:44,760 --> 00:56:49,000
Emily's point was like, "Every single woman let 
a sigh of relief. Finally, someone said the quiet  

697
00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:56,240
part out loud." There is a tremendous advantage to 
understanding that one part of the market already  

698
00:56:57,600 --> 00:57:00,840
has an Overton window that's different 
from the mainstream market. Then you can  

699
00:57:00,840 --> 00:57:03,800
appeal to that, and they will respect you for it.

700
00:57:03,800 --> 00:57:11,040
Amazing. These are 11 very concrete ways to think 
about ways to get above the noise, get people's  

701
00:57:11,040 --> 00:57:16,960
attention, be a little subversive. There's always 
this talk about thinking from first principles  

702
00:57:16,960 --> 00:57:21,760
and thinking outside the box and being innovative 
and creative. I love that you have put together,  

703
00:57:21,760 --> 00:57:29,400
"Here's the 11 ways that people do it." How do you 
suggest people use this? Is it like get a room,  

704
00:57:29,400 --> 00:57:32,760
get some people together, brainstorm and 
go through this list? Any advice on just  

705
00:57:32,760 --> 00:57:36,840
how to operationalize, coming up with 
ideas knowing that they have this list.

706
00:57:38,320 --> 00:57:42,920
This is somewhat magic. It takes a lot of 
time. It's a skill you can learn. It's a  

707
00:57:42,920 --> 00:57:48,800
muscle you develop. I would say spend some 
time thinking about how to be disagreeable,  

708
00:57:48,800 --> 00:57:54,480
understanding the system you're in, and then 
use the need for novelty and disagreeability  

709
00:57:54,480 --> 00:58:00,600
to temporarily let yourself think like a super 
villain. We have some tactics for this: ignoring  

710
00:58:00,600 --> 00:58:06,320
the guardrails, embracing absurdity, not pulling 
your punches on wording. I've had people go,  

711
00:58:06,320 --> 00:58:10,800
"Oh, I can't possibly do that in my marketing."
Remember Blair Witch? Remember The Blair Witch  

712
00:58:10,800 --> 00:58:18,200
Project? They literally killed their actors, 
well, not literally. But according to the web,  

713
00:58:18,200 --> 00:58:22,600
they had people out there trying to find 
the actors. They listed them as missing on  

714
00:58:22,600 --> 00:58:29,680
their movie page. They did literally starve 
their actors. They actually underfed them,  

715
00:58:29,680 --> 00:58:33,320
and they played weird scary noises outside their 
tent at night. They even gave them conflicting  

716
00:58:33,320 --> 00:58:38,480
information. They got so much attention because 
they were hyperbolic about how they positioned  

717
00:58:38,480 --> 00:58:43,840
things. Wes Kao talks about the spiky point 
of view. I think those are super important. 

718
00:58:43,840 --> 00:58:46,160
There are some other techniques that we 
found. There's this really interesting  

719
00:58:46,160 --> 00:58:53,240
innovation formula called TRIZ, which is a 
