750
01:01:35,040 --> 01:01:40,120
I do a lot of work in digital government with this 
conference called FWD50. Last year, I told people,  

751
01:01:40,800 --> 01:01:46,680
when you're launching a battleship, you can't 
push a software update and change the hull.  

752
01:01:46,680 --> 01:01:52,000
It's shipping. So you take the risky parts, 
and you put them at the end. As a result,  

753
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:55,960
you write the spec up front, and then you do 
the plan for testing and all this other stuff.  

754
01:01:55,960 --> 01:02:02,320
But the entire pattern, every pattern we have 
in the Western world for mass production of  

755
01:02:02,320 --> 01:02:05,800
something, whether that's software development 
or shooting a movie or building a battleship,  

756
01:02:05,800 --> 01:02:11,040
you do the easily changed stuff up front. You 
can change a feature in the spec in a day,  

757
01:02:11,040 --> 01:02:16,160
you can change it in the code in a week, you can 
change it in production, if at all, in a month. So  

758
01:02:16,160 --> 01:02:22,280
thinking about what's scarce and what's abundant, 
what's hard and what's easy generally informs the  

759
01:02:22,280 --> 01:02:29,480
process that we use to deliver any product to 
market. We do not step back and say, what has  

760
01:02:29,480 --> 01:02:35,920
technology done to change the relative risk and 
the relative fungibility of each of those steps? 

761
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:43,600
If I'm building software, it may now be easier 
to use an LLM and Figma to build 10 prototypes,  

762
01:02:43,600 --> 01:02:48,800
show them to citizens in government, see which 
ones they like, and then document the one that  

763
01:02:48,800 --> 01:02:54,600
works. Because now documenting the thing well 
that works is the risky part. That's actually  

764
01:02:54,600 --> 01:02:58,960
the harder part because that's what's going to 
get passed by legislators and stuff. So just  

765
01:02:58,960 --> 01:03:02,560
because we used to write a spec in the right 
code doesn't mean that's how we should do it.  

766
01:03:02,560 --> 01:03:09,560
I think for any organization, reevaluating the 
processes that you assume are correct based on  

767
01:03:09,560 --> 01:03:15,640
what technology has made hard or easy, that's 
how big companies fail and small companies win.

